<recipeml version="0.5">
  <recipe>
    <head>
      <title>Vindaloo (Bindaloo)</title>
      <categories>
        <cat>None</cat></categories>
      <yield>1</yield></head>
    <ingredients>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>2</qty>
          <unit>pounds</unit></amt>
        <item>Pork; beef or a duck</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>6</qty>
          <unit>ounces</unit></amt>
        <item>Mustard oil</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1</qty>
          <unit>tablespoon</unit></amt>
        <item>Mashed garlic</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1</qty>
          <unit>tablespoon</unit></amt>
        <item>Ground ginger (or sub. fresh)</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1</qty>
          <unit>teaspoon</unit></amt>
        <item>Ground chilli - if you're cooking for your aged Auntie.</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1</qty>
          <unit>teaspoon</unit></amt>
        <item>Ground coriander</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1/2</qty>
          <unit>teaspoons</unit></amt>
        <item>Ground cummin</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>2</qty>
          <unit/></amt>
        <item>Bay leaves (up to 3)</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>12</qty>
          <unit/></amt>
        <item>Peppercorns</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>6</qty>
          <unit/></amt>
        <item>Cloves; ground</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>5</qty>
          <unit/></amt>
        <item>Cardamoms; ground</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>6</qty>
          <unit/></amt>
        <item>2-inch sticks cinnamon; ground</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>4</qty>
          <unit>ounces</unit></amt>
        <item>Malt vinegar (In the US that's the brown stuff sold as English "Pub" vinegar)</item></ing>
      <ing>
        <amt>
          <qty>1/2</qty>
          <unit>teaspoons</unit></amt>
        <item>Salt</item></ing></ingredients>
    <directions>
      <step>  Cut the meat into suitable sized bits. Mix in the vinegar, all ground
  spices and the salt and throw into the fridge until next day (or the day
  after). Heat the oil in a thick bottomed pan, toss in the meat mixture,
  plus peppercorns and bay leaves, and simmer gently for two hours until the
  meat is tender. Eat.
  
  P.S. I'll be making some later this week using lamb trimmings left over
  from Easter. Drop me a line if you want to know what I did. Also I tend to
  be a bit more heavy-handed with the spices than above. Posted to
  CHILE-HEADS DIGEST V4 #038 by Jim Tidwell &lt;snd1jlt@snd10.med.navy.mil&gt; on
  Jul 24, 1997
 
</step></directions></recipe></recipeml>
